
@startuml

' Define classes and their relationships
class Student {
    +String name
    +String studentId
    +List<Course> registeredCourses
    +makeAppointment(Course, TeachingAssistant, DateTime): Appointment
}

class TeachingAssistant {
    +String name
    +String taId
    +List<Course> assignedCourses
    +scheduleAppointment(Student, Course, DateTime): Appointment
}

class Course {
    +String courseCode
    +String title
    +List<Student> enrolledStudents
    +List<TeachingAssistant> tas
}

class Appointment {
    +DateTime time
    +Student student
    +TeachingAssistant ta
    +Course course
}

' Relationships
Student "1" -- "0..*" Course : is registered for
Course "1" -- "0..*" TeachingAssistant : has TA(s)
TeachingAssistant "1" -- "0..*" Course : teaches
Student "1" -- "0..*" Appointment : participates in
TeachingAssistant "1" -- "0..*" Appointment : schedules with
Appointment "1" -- "1" Course : related to
Appointment "1" -- "1" TeachingAssistant : with
Appointment "1" -- "1" Student : by

@enduml

---

### Explanation of Key Points:
- **Student** can only make appointments if they are **registered for a course**.
- **TeachingAssistant** can only schedule appointments for **courses they are assigned to**.
- An **Appointment** is always tied to one **Student**, one **TeachingAssistant**, and one **Course**.
- Relationships ensure **validity constraints** (e.g., a student cannot book an appointment for a course they are not registered in).

